Quarterly Reports

State of GEODNET Q1 2025

Armita

Jun 9, 2025 ⋅  9 min read

Key Insights

  • The number of active Satellite Miners surpassed 14,000, with city-level coverage up 235% QoQ and country-level coverage rising 47%, signaling renewed global deployment.
  • GEOD token burns reached 2.25 million, up 17% QoQ, and had a total value of $646,300, reflecting rising demand for Real-Time Kinematic (RTK) data services and consistent monetization progress.
  • GEODNET’s circulating market cap rose 36% QoQ to $82 million as GEOD price increased 8.6% to $0.26.
  • GEODNET secured an $8 million strategic round led by Multicoin Capital, aimed at accelerating infrastructure deployment, particularly in robotics, autonomous systems, and underserved regions.
  • GEODNET launched the GEO-PULSE consumer GPS device and announced integrations with Septentrio, Bad Elf, and other hardware partners, broadening its reach across enterprise GNSS solutions and AI-driven applications.

Primer

GEODNET (Global Earth Observation Decentralized Network) is a Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Network (DePIN) project delivering high-precision geospatial data and positioning through a decentralized Real-Time Kinematics (RTK) network. The network operates on a community-driven model where individual operators purchase and install RTK Base Stations, also known as Satellite Miners, on their property. Satellite Miners receive Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) signals and provide real-time correction data with 1 cm accuracy, which is then transmitted to GEODNET's cloud platform.

The GEOD token is the utility token of the GEODNET network and is primarily deployed on Polygon, with multichain support recently extended to Solana via Wormhole. GEOD is primarily used to reward users who have installed Satellite Miners and to pay for RTK data services. Additionally, GEOD tokens enable participation in project governance.

Since its launch in December 2021, GEODNET has expanded to over 14,000 RTK Base Stations globally. This rapid growth has resulted in $2 million in annualized revenue. For a full primer on GEODNET, refer to our Initiation of Coverage report.

Key Metrics

Analysis

GEODNET GEOD’s circulating market capitalization reached $82 million in Q1 2025, marking a 36% QoQ increase. Its fully diluted valuation remained relatively flat at $250 million, based on a maximum supply of 1 billion tokens. By the end of the quarter, 46% (up from 40% in Q4 2024) of the total supply had been unlocked. For the first half of 2025, GEOD tokens are unlocking at a rate of 21 million per month.

GEODNET operates on a decentralized model where individual participants deploy RTK Base Stations, known as Satellite Miners, on their property. These base stations receive GNSS signals and generate real-time correction data with centimeter-level accuracy, which is transmitted to GEODNET's cloud platform. In exchange, operators receive daily GEOD token rewards. In Q1 2025, GEODNET had over 2,700 new active miners, a 22% QoQ increase from 2,200 in Q4 2024.

The network also surpassed 14,000 active Satellite Miners worldwide, reinforcing its position as the world’s largest RTK network, surpassing centralized providers such as Trimble in scale.

Source

GEODNET's infrastructure spans more than 140 countries and 4,000 cities. The highest concentration of miners is in the United States and Europe, with a significant presence in South America, Australia, and India.

In Q1 2025, GEODNET's geographical coverage began to rebound after hitting a low in the previous quarter. The number of cities with active Satellite Miners rose to 328, a 235% QoQ increase from 98 in Q4 2024. Country-level coverage also improved, reaching 47 countries, up 47% QoQ from 32. This recovery, while still below earlier highs, suggests that renewed funding, hardware integrations, and visibility from CES 2025 played a role in reaccelerating global deployment.

The GEODNET Foundation monetizes correction data by selling it through multiple channels, with 80% of the revenue allocated to buying and burning GEOD tokens. GEOD tokens also serve as an indirect payment mechanism within the network. While most RTK data transactions are conducted in fiat currency, 80% of these payments are used to repurchase and burn GEOD tokens, while the remaining 20% is directed to the GEODNET Foundation.

In Q1 2025, the volume of GEOD tokens burned reached 2.3 million, a 17% QoQ increase, with a total value of $646,300, up 39% QoQ. This continued rise in token burns indicates growing revenue from RTK data sales. While burn volumes remain on an upward trend, the rate of growth has moderated, suggesting a more stable phase of network usage and monetization.

The total supply of GEOD tokens is capped at 1 billion, with no plans for additional issuance. Mining rewards are distributed daily to base station operators according to a fixed schedule. Allocations for the team, investors, and ecosystem follow a multi-year vesting plan. A detailed breakdown is available in our Initiation of Coverage report.

In Q1 2025, GEODNET’s total token unlocks reached 462.8 million, reflecting an increase of 61.3 million tokens unlocked compared to the previous quarter.

Ecosystem and Partnerships

Geodnet is expanding its ecosystem through strategic partnerships across industries, enhancing Real-Time Kinematic (RTK) capabilities and extending its reach.

Funding Strategy

$8 Million Strategic Raise: In February 2025, GEODNET secured $8 million in a strategic funding round led by Multicoin Capital, with participation from ParaFi Capital and Digital Asset Capital Management. This round was positioned to accelerate GEODNET’s efforts in deploying its real-time RTK infrastructure, particularly for robotics and autonomous systems. The funding aims to enhance GEODNET’s service offerings in precision navigation and support integrations across industries like logistics, agriculture, and drone-based delivery. According to project leadership, part of the funds will also be used to scale deployments of RTK base stations in underserved regions.

Product Development and Hardware Launch

GEO-PULSE Launch: GEODNET introduced the GEO-PULSE, a GPS receiver priced at $149 designed to provide 10 cm-level positioning accuracy using the GEODNET RTK network. The device connects via Bluetooth and is intended for developers and consumer applications such as navigation, fleet optimization, and robotics. The company also previewed an SDK expected in Q2 2025 to allow developers to integrate GEO-PULSE into broader applications. GEO-PULSE is GEODNET’s first consumer-targeted device, designed to broaden access to precision GNSS beyond industrial users

Septentrio Integration: In January 2025, Septentrio, a leading provider of GNSS receivers, added GEODNET to its Agnostic Corrections Partner Program. This enables Septentrio devices to access GEODNET’s RTK correction services, providing users with more flexibility in achieving high-precision geolocation across applications such as surveying, precision agriculture, and automation.

Bad Elf Partnership: In January 2025, GEODNET partnered with GPS hardware manufacturer Bad Elf to provide a multi-year RTK service plan for its Flex and Flex Mini devices. The integration eliminates the need for manual credential management and simplifies access to centimeter-level GPS accuracy for users in fields like GIS mapping and mobile surveying.

Ongoing Integrations and Partnerships

  • Wingbits Collaboration: Geodnet partnered with Wingbits, a decentralized flight-tracking network, to develop professional-grade ADS-B and RemoteID tracking nodes. Wingbits' network currently has 2,000 ADS-B stations, with plans to grow to 10,000 by 2025. GEODNET's RTK service enhances the accuracy of Wingbits' nodes, improving air traffic monitoring and drone operations.
  • Propeller Integration: Propeller, a worksite mapping company, integrated GEODNET's GNSS stations to enhance survey-grade mapping for industries like construction and mining. Using data from GEODNET's 9,000 GNSS reference stations, Propeller delivers high-accuracy maps to support global worksites, improving decision-making.
  • Quectel Wireless Solutions Collaboration: Quectel Wireless Solutions is leveraging GEODNET's GNSS modules to target a wide range of IoT applications, including scooters and robotic mowers.
  • ByNav Integration: ByNav has integrated GEODNET'S RTK services into its Automotive Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS) solutions. This collaboration enhances precision and safety in autonomous driving applications.
  • Multichain Expansion: GEODNET launched the GEOD token on Solana using Wormhole’s Native Token Transfers (NTT) framework.

Events and Public Speaking

CES 2025 Presence: At CES 2025, GEODNET launched the GEO-PULSE device and highlighted new integrations with enterprise GNSS manufacturers. The company also used the event to strengthen its positioning as a decentralized infrastructure provider for high-precision navigation across hardware and AI robotics sectors.

Policy and Industry Outreach: In January 2025, GEODNET founder Mike Horton spoke at DePIN Day Seattle about the network’s role in AI, robotics, and decentralized infrastructure. On March 27, he also demonstrated GEODNET’s real-time RTK and flight-tracking capabilities to U.S. policymakers using a dual-mining device with Wingbits on Capitol Hill.

Podcast & Media Features: In Q1 2025, Mike Horton appeared on several podcasts to discuss GEODNET’s infrastructure and real-world applications. On Unleashing DePIN (January 8), he outlined the network’s decentralized model; on Andy and Friends (February 14), he highlighted use cases in autonomous vehicles and agriculture.

Ecosystem growth (Q2 2025)

GEODNET expanded its ecosystem in Q2 2025 through several strategic partnerships and integrations across GNSS hardware, robotics, AI, and autonomous driving:

  • Frodobots Collaboration: Frodobots unveiled the EarthRover Mini+, a consumer robot using GEODNET RTK-enabled GPS to collect real-world data for AI training.
  • ROVR Protocol Investment: GEODNET co-led a $2.6 million seed round in ROVR Network, which builds HD maps using lidar, cameras, and RTK data. ROVR will burn 20% of its data sales revenue in GEOD tokens, linking GEODNET usage to token value.
  • GEOD Mining Support on Solana: GEODNET activated mining support on Solana, allowing miners to earn GEOD directly on the chain. This move reduces transaction costs and expands multichain accessibility.
  • GIP-6 Governance Proposal Passed: GEODNET passed GIP-6, a governance proposal introducing performance-based incentives to improve the consistency and quality of RTK stations. The mechanism enhances data reliability without increasing token emissions.

Closing Summary

In Q1 2025, GEODNET advanced its position as the world’s largest decentralized RTK network, reaching over 14,000 active Satellite Miners and covering 328 cities across 47 countries, a strong recovery from the prior quarter. The network’s circulating market capitalization rose to $82 million, up 36% QoQ, while token burns increased to 2.25 million GEOD, reflecting growing data monetization. Backed by an $8 million strategic raise led by Multicoin Capital, GEODNET accelerated infrastructure deployment, particularly in robotics, agriculture, and underserved regions. The launch of GEO-PULSE, along with integrations with Septentrio, Bad Elf, and ongoing collaborations with Wingbits, Propeller, and ByNav, extended GEODNET’s reach across enterprise and consumer GNSS applications. Public visibility through CES 2025, industry partnerships, and policy engagement contributed to renewed ecosystem momentum, positioning GEODNET for continued growth as a foundational layer for decentralized geolocation infrastructure.
